thoughts.a: Input grid and output grid are the same sizes. Input grid contains black color background and a variety of different shapes and colored objects all inside of red 5x5 bounding boxes. Those bounding boxes and objects are located on a bigger, larger blue bounding box and all intersect the blue bounding box in some way. We notice the output grid is extremely similar to the input grid, but with the exception that certain colors have been swapped. The shapes that exist inside of the red bounding boxes are all the same in the output grid as the input grid. However, the colors of those objects are now different. In the input grid, there was a pink plus sign in the top bounding box, but now there is a green plus sign in the exact location. Note in the output grid, we have pink, green, and aqua colored shapes, and those are the same colors present in the objects in the output grid as well, but they have all been rotated by one placement in the counterclockwise direction. Thus, the hypothesis is the following. Input grid will have a black color background and a large blue bounding box. intersecting with this large blue bounding box will be some number of red bounding boxes. These red bounding boxes will contain some object of some shape and color inside of them. In order to construct the output grid, we need to copy over the input grid exactly as is, with the exception of rotating the colors of the objects inside the bounding boxes that intersect the larger blue bounding box by one placement in the counterclockwise direction. Note that we don't rotate the shapes of the objects, just the colors of the objects to the next shape.
thoughts.b: The input grid contains a black colored background and a variety of different shapes and colored objects all inside of red 5x5 bounding boxes. These bounding boxes and objects are located on a larger blue bounding box that intersects the blue bounding box is some way. According to the hypothesis, in order to construct the output grid, we need to rotate the colors of the objects that are internal of the red bounding boxes by one placement in the counterclockwise direction. Note that the shapes of the internal objects do not move, but only the colors, and only one position in the circular blue bounding box path in the counterclockwise direction. The rest of the input grid is copied over as is. Because this is what we see in the input grid, the hypothesis holds.
thoughts.c: The input grid again contains a black color background and a variety of different shapes and colored objects all inside of red bounding boxes. Because this is exactly what we see in the output grid, the hypothesis holds.
thoughts.d: We apply the hypothesis here. Input Grid contains a black color background and a variety of different shapes and colored objects all inside of red bounding boxes. Each of these red bounding boxes intersects and overlaps a larger blue bounding box in the input grid. According to the hypothesis, we need to copy over the input grid to the output grid exactly as is, with the exception of moving the colors by one placement in the counter-clockwise direction. Remember that according to the hypothesis, the shapes of the objects themselves do not move, but instead just the colors of the interior objects. This relative placement dictates the circular order to the rotation.
